beers.beerDescription: St. Brigid's Day (Mary of the Gael) is celebrated in Ireland at the time of Imbolic, a once pagan celebration of "Summer in the Belly of Winter." This release in our series of seasonal saisons is a refreshingly hoppy take on saison for springtime. Mary of the Gael has a simple base of pilsner malt, a touch of honey malt, and is dry hopped with a copious amount of floral hops.
Farmhouse ale with cranberries
Uncarbonated "still" ale, fermented with three strains of yeast and aged in American oak.
This New England version of an imperial stout is brewed with Massachusetts malted wheat and native Massachusetts yeast.
A citrusy and tropical farmhouse ale.
Saison with Ethiopian single origin coffee, made in collaboration with George Howell Coffee
Pale ale with Amarillo and Mosaic hops
Farmhouse Ale brewed with native yeast cultures from Maine lowbush Blubeeries.
Flor De Varenne is a blend of barrel-fermented wild ales produced using a blend of our house yeast, Renaud, lactobacillus and a house-blended selection of brettanomyces.

Hoppy saison with a blend of three new hops from NZ and AU. So named simply because it reminded Bryan of "Fantasia on Greensleeves." 
Only available on draft at the brewery.
Black saison with star anise and gentian root, brewed in collaboration with Stillwater Artisanal.

MysticBrewery.name: Mystic
MysticBrewery.breweryDescription: Producer of American farmhouse, abbey, and wild ales. Restoring the art of fermentation to its proper place since 2011 in Chelsea, Massachusetts.

beers.beerDescription: A not very bitter beer at all, the ESB has a smooth, malty initial mouthful that transitions to a marmalade like fruitiness from the East Kent Goldings hop variety. Toffee and light dried fruit notes.
Piney, resinous & brilliant.  Moderate bitterness from this brownish red IPA is perfect for post-summer porch sitting.
Solid malt with hard candy sweetness. Big grapefruit notes, hints of lime and tropics from Citra kettle and dry hopping. Tightly wound with dark super fruit character from our Belgian yeast.

Dark brown with Chestnut highlights. Roasted coffee and chocolate aroma. Super smooth, complex palate from de-bittered dark malts, German hops, and our house lager yeast. Originally brewed in the Baltic region and rooted in British Porter tradition, taking cues from Russian Imperial Stout. Warming alcohol with a bold, lingering finish. 7.4 ABV
Berliner Weisse, the “people’s champagne”. Tart and crisp.  Highly effervescent with sparkling wine notes and a crackery malt finish. Try with raspberry or woodruff syrup for a fun addition.
A traditional German smoked lager (Rauchbier), with 33% Beechwood smoked malt. Sweet doughy malt finish with subtle smoke throughout. 6.5% ABV
Fully bright and deep golden fall classic. Brewed with Vienna and Pilsner malts with a malty sweetness.

Festivus for the rest of us! A German Starkbier traditionally brewed for the holidays. Dominant malt flavors with some candied fruit notes. Noticeable alcohol. The German equivalent of English Barleywine. Perfect for feats of strength and airing of grievances!

A Brown Porter aged on Cocoa Nibs. Sweet chocolate syrup aroma with roast coffee notes. Fairly light bodied, with a rich, lingering finish of semi-sweet chocolate and roasted malt flavors. ABV: 5.3% B_ Su_e _o dri_k y_ur O_a_tin_!

Perfect golden straw color, our version of the Pilsner
is bursting with grassy herbal notes from Noble
German Hallertauer and Czech Saaz hops. Refreshing bitterness gives way to a crisp malt finish.

This Coffee Milk Stout collaboration beer is made
even more luscious with the addition of lactose. The
single origin coffee beans, from Flight Coffee Co,
Bedford, NH, bring a tart berry flavor that contrasts
nicely with the dark chocolate notes from the malt. Contains caffeine and lactose.
Traditional German wheat beer brewed with rye malt
Our Savin Summer Stout, but fermented with American Ale yeast & a healthy dose of Chinook hops, lending pine & fruit notes to this dry roasty classic.

Barrel-Aged Wheat Ale made with 90% Wheat malt with Flaked Oats and Carafoam. Bittered, flavored and dry hopped with Columbus hops. Aged 2+ months in Jamaican Rum barrels with fresh pineapple and house-toasted coconut. 5% ABV
Deep golden IPA. Grainy malt balance with a hint of sweetness. Bracing carbonation and bitterness, hints of carmel aroma.
This rusty, reddish brown beer has a lasting tan foam with a sweet, stone fruit aroma and flavor. You'll taste a mild malt presence with nutty spice and caramel notes. Clocks in at 6.9% ABV.
Another take on the Berliner style. Clean ale yeast. Slightly tart with a crackery wheat snap.

beers.beerName: Stove By A Whale - Barrel Aged
beers.beerDescription: Limited release of our Stove by a Whale that has been barrel aged in Woodford barrels. Dark brown with Chestnut highlights. Roasted coffee and chocolate aroma. Super smooth, complex palate from de-bittered dark malts, German hops, and our house lager yeast. Originally brewed in the Baltic region and rooted in British Porter tradition, taking cues from Russian Imperial Stout. Warming alcohol with a bold, lingering finish. ABV 7.4%

A pale, hazy lager brewed with an over abundance of hops, 3 lbs per barrel of American hops (Citra, Mosaic,El Dorado) in the whirlpool and 3 lbs per barrel for dry hopping (2/3rd Hallertauer Tradition and 1/3 Citra).  5.5% ABV

DorchesterBrewingCompany.name: Dorchester Brewing Co.
DorchesterBrewingCompany.breweryDescription:
Dorchester Brewing Company is a partner brewing facility in Dorchester, MA, right in the heart of Boston. When you visit our brewery, you’ll enjoy more than your typical tasting room. Our 20 line tap system is filled with a wide variety of fresh craft beer including our house beers, local brewing partners and regional collaborators on tap for all to consume and taste. Fresh, new, innovative, trendy beers. Try a tasting flight or full pours and grab fresh beer to go!

Our Tap Room is welcome to anyone that wants to visit – beer nerds, beer novices, families, children, people who would rather work here enjoying some beers then at their home offices! We’ve got plenty of games for all to enjoy, wi-fi, food trucks, as well as merchandise and fresh beer to go. We look forward to sharing our love of beer with everyone!

www.dorchesterbrewing.com

reviews.text: I don't know why we hadn't done this on all our previous visits to Boston. It was actually a lot of fun. Very informative and funny. The guys did a great job, it was very interactive. And of course the favorite part, the sampling of beers! There's plenty of parking and there was even some stands out on the side of the brewery with fresh produce and other goods.

Funny, short and informative tour of the Sam Adams brewery.  This is where they invent their new flavors, not where they actually produce the beer for major distribution. Definitely worth a stop - if not for the free tour then for the free beer ;)

The tour was wonderful! The tour itself was "free", with a $2 suggested donation for local charities. The second part of the tour was a beer tasting. We were all given generous samples of 4 different beers, and we're allowed to keep our glasses as souvenirs. The trip out here was definitely worthwhile!
Jeff was in the majority of our tour and great... it's free and you get beer so not sure how to give this less than 5 stars. Only hour and informative enough to not put you to sleep

Not bad. Guinness is better soooo far!! 
The tour is not long but they have no system production in comparison with the Guinness. 
Free entrance and tour,  free degustation of beer and they give you the glass as a gift. 
The Gift Shop, small and not too much products to choose. Guinness shop: amazing. 
The beer: excellent.
Free tour with awesome guides. The tour will show you around the place and give you some samples of yeast and other ingredients used in making the beer....

beers.beerDescription: Samuel Adams Boston Lager® is the best example of the fundamental characteristics of a great beer, offering a full, rich flavor that is both balanced and complex. It is brewed using a decoration mash, a time consuming, traditional four vessel brewing process discarded by many contemporary brewers. This process brings forth a rich sweetness from the malt that makes it well worth the effort. Samuel Adams Boston Lager® also uses only the finest of ingredients including two row barley, as well as German Noble aroma hops. The exclusive use of two row barley not only imparts a full, smooth body but also gives the beer a wide spectrum of malt flavor ranging from slightly sweet to caramel to slightly roasted. The Noble hops varieties, Hallertau Mittelfruh and Tettnang Tettnanger, add a wide range of floral, piney and citrus notes, which are present from the aroma, through the flavor, to the lingering smooth finish. We take great pride in the Noble hops used in our beers. They are hand selected by Jim Koch and our other brewers from the world's oldest hops growing area. Among the world's most expensive, they cost twenty times as much as other hops.

In 1810, the Oktoberfest tradition was born when Munich celebrated the Crown Prince’s wedding with a special beer and 16 day party. Our version of this classic style blends rich malts for a hearty, smooth flavor with notes of caramel creating a brew that’s perfect for the season, or whatever you’re celebrating.

Samuel Adams® Summer Ale is an American wheat ale. This hazy golden unfiltered brew combines crisp wheat with the bright citrus of lemon peel and the subtle spice of Grains of Paradise.  This rare African pepper, closely related to cardamom, was first used as a brewing spice in the 13th Century and adds just the right peppery kick. All of these flavors come together to create a thirst quenching and utterly refreshing brew perfect for those warm summer days.

Bold and rich, with a touch of holiday spice
The first thing one notices in a Samuel Adams® Winter Lager is its color: the deep brown of winter. Then comes the magical aroma which promises something special on the tongue. The warm aroma of cinnamon and ginger which blends with the toasty sweetness of the malted barley and hint of citrus.
Brewed with 5 varieties of west coast hops cascade, simcoe, centennial, chinook & amarillo. Big citrus & grapefruit  flavors with subtle pine notes for a flavorful refreshing brew.
A White Ale brewed with a blend of fresh ground spring spices including orange, plum, and fresh ground coriander.

Perfect for any summer day, Samuel Adams® Porch Rocker was inspired by traditional Bavarian Radlers that mix beer with German-style lemonade.  For our bright and citrusy Radler, we blended a Helles beer with lemon for a fresh-squeezed lemon taste, effervescent sweetness, and slightly tart, refreshing finish.  A light malt character and hint of hops balance out this summer brew.

As crisp as the first snowfall of the year, this unfiltered white ale is blended with holiday spices including cinnamon, nutmeg, and orange peel.  The familiar citrus and wheat characters of the ale are complemented by the warmth of the spices for a festive brew that’s perfect for the season.

Ale brewed with Cherries, crisp and fruity with a hint of honey.  Samuel Adams Cherry Wheat® follows the centuries old American tradition of brewing beer with native ingredients, in this case Michigan cherries as well as a touch of honey. The sweet fruitiness of the cherries is balanced against the crisp, cereal note from the malted wheat and the subtle citrus flavor from the Noble hops. The end result is a sweet, refreshing beer that is light on the palate but long on complexity.

Spicy and Bold, a big Christmas cookie of a beer.
Samuel Adams® Old Fezziwig® Ale is the Christmas cookie of beer. Bursting with spices of the season and a remarkably full body, it helps those long winter nights pass much quicker. The full body hits the palate first with a depth of malt character ranging from sweeter toffee and caramel notes to the more dark, roasty chocolate notes. Then come the spices in full force. Cinnamon, ginger and orange peel dance on the tongue bringing with them the celebratory spirit that goes hand in hand with the season.
This double IPA is big, brewed with over 5 lbs per barrel of American and Australian hops, and packed with fruity, citrus, pine, and resin notes for a bold hop finish. Cheers!

Brewed with real grapefruit for an added punch of citrusy goodness that amplifies the tropical fruit and citrus notes from the hops.  A hint of juiciness rounds out the bitterness and brings a refreshing finish to this bold, bright, thirst-quenching IPA.

A unique brew that combinines the intense hop character of an IPA with the crisp spicy wheat character of a Belgian-style white ale. The white ale and IPA combination make this crisp, smooth, yet hop-friendly beer the perfect pairing with a variety of meats and cheeses. Brewed with apricots and spices.

This dark beer has a big, malty character with the added sweetness of chocolate. Chocolate Bock is slowly aged on a bed of rare dark cocoa nibs, the primary ingredient in chocolate. Known for their quality, these cocoa nibs harvested in Ecuador, impart complex aromas and flavors from chocolaty to fruity, nutty, earthy, and citrusy.

A crisp, refreshing version of a traditional Belgian beer. Fruity, slightly spicy flavors from the Belgian yeast are balanced by toffee and caramel notes from our blend of malts. The hops provide a citrus character that rounds out this enjoyable brew.
Our take on the classic hybrid style from Cologne Germany, Escape Route combines the subtle fruit notes of an ale with the smooth crispness of a lager for a bright, refreshing brew.

Samuel Adams Noble Pils is one of the only brews made with all five Noble hops from the worldâ€™s growing regions. its bright flavor and lively, citrus hop character reminds us that the warm days of spring are just a few weeks away.

beers.beerName: Samuel Adams Merry Maker Gingerbread Stout
beers.beerDescription: Gingerbread stout brewed with cinnamon, cloves, nutmeg, and ginger as well as well as East Kent Goldings & Fuggles hops
The distinct hop character of an IPA in a smooth lager.  The hops in this brew lend a bright grapefruit, citrus, floral aroma and flavor with a refreshing, crisp lager finish.

Amber, smooth, and resinous, this ale was inspired by our exploration of Australian hops.  We discovered that their rugged, spicy and piney character brightened a back-bone of roasted caramel malts, creating a beer with surprising depth and smoothness.

Malty and slightly sweet, balanced by earthy notes from the hops.  The gentle rain and fertile soil of Ireland helped inspire this style of ale, known for being remarkably balanced. Pale and Caramel malts give the beer its rich, deep red color and distinctive caramel flavor. The sweetness of the malt is pleasantly balanced by a pronounced hop bitterness and an earthy note from the East Kent Goldings hops. Samuel Adams® Irish Red finishes smooth and leaves you wanting to take another sip.

WHITE CAPPED AND LIVELY – the frothy white head of this distinctive nitro brew softly cascades into bright gold.   The first sip reveals a smooth velvety taste with a light wheat character and hints of orange while an undercurrent of peppery spice adds a bright finish.

A laidback golden pilsner that’s full of character.  The fun of brewing is that it’s always evolving, even in the world’s most popular beer style, the pilsner, there’s still room for creativity.  For our German Pilsner we wanted to showcase both new & heritage hops from the original hop gardens of Bavaria.  The classic Noble hops offer a floral spiciness while the new varieties create a fruity & citrusy character for an elegant, light bodied yet flavorful brew.
A fresh take on a traditional Belgian-style white ale, brewed with orange & tangerine peel, coriander, & grains of paradise for a crisp, citrusy brew with a hint of spice.
Blueberry Hill Lager is a blueberry kellerbier style beer. Look for it exclusively in the Beer of Summer variety pack (2013) and on draft for special events.

SamuelAdamsBrewery.name: Boston Beer Company
SamuelAdamsBrewery.breweryDescription:
Jim Koch founded the Boston Beer Company back in 1984 after brewing the first batch of Samuel Adams Boston Lager in his kitchen. It was his mission to reshape the way American beer drinkers thought of American beer. 

Just six weeks after introducing Samuel Adams Boston Lager to the public, it brought home the "Best Beer in America" honors at the Great American Beer Festival in Denver. An honor it went on to win 3 more times before that particular award was discontinued.

Today, Samuel Adams makes more than 21 styles of award winning beer and is recognized around the globe as a hot house of new beer ideas.

If you share our passion, join us here as a fan! 

Cheers!

The Boston Beer Company, Boston MA

userTips.tip: "I keep asking for my own flavor of Sam Adams, and they keep telling me that 'Bubblegum Cough Syrup' would never sell." - Conan O'Brien
Free tours and tastings at the brewery between 10 a.m. and 3 p.m. Mon. - Thurs., plus Saturdays (the tours leave every 45 minutes or so). On Fridays, tours continue through 5:30 p.m.
Take a fun and informative tour through the Samuel Adams Brewery. Plus free beer is part of the tour.
FREE brewery tour, FREE beer tastings, and a FREE tasting glass - how can you go wrong?
Go to Sam Adams Brewery, take the tour, get some free beer.
When you go they'll generally give you three different beers. The first two are the Boston Lager and the current Seasonal beer. The third changes and is usually something unique and/or special.
Don't hog the pitchers!
Mail out a postcard for free from the gift shop.  Stay near the back of the tour on the third stop (the large steel barrel room) to get a prime seat in the tasting room.
If visiting from out of town, take the T to get there.  The mileage isn't far, but by foot you pass through some "interesting" neighborhoods.
Go on a brewery tour to learn all about the beer making process. Oh, and to sample!
The tour is free and you get to sample three beers and keep the tasting glass. The tour guide was really funny and entertaining. Lots of fun! Go to Doyle's for food and keep your Sam Adams glass.

Tour informativo de uma das melhores cervejas que existem. Além de uma boa cerveja, você degusta 3 tipos e leva um copo. Não paga nada, mas vale uma donation. No final do tour vc acaba na loja show!!!

reviews.text: Fun brewery! Great people working there and very cool location. Beer is awesome and pretzels are delicious. Check out the Boston skyline from the taproom and even the bathroom! Parking wasn't as bad as I was expecting. Definitely can't wait to go back again!

Great place to check out when in Boston. Awesome beer selection and the pretzels with dipping sauce are amazing, and that's coming from someone who is not big into pretzels. They offer many different beer flights so you can sample many different beers before you commit. Downsides are that there is almost always a long wait to get in on the weekends and that it is very crowded once inside, but they can't really help that other than expanding. Overall would recommend you check this place out, even if you are not a huge beer drinker.

Nice, fun place. Good selection of beer, and the pretzels were very good.

Tour was also a lot of fun. The two tour guides did a great job. Very informative and very entertaining.

Awesome brewery, definitely a must do. The tours sell out fast on weekends, so either get there early or go on a weekday. I wasn't a beer drinker until I came here. The pretzels and dipping sauces are amazing.
Absolutely my favorite brewery to date! The Harpoon IPA is my favorite IPA I've ever had. Would definitely recommend the tour if you have time.

This was my favorite brewery that I visited on my last trip to Boston.
The bar area was massive in size with plenty of space with everyone to enjoy a beer...

beers.beerDescription:
We started brewing this beer as a summer seasonal in 1993.  There were some great IPAs out in the Pacific Northwest, but no local IPAs on the east coast.  We wanted to have a local IPA, so we brewed one.  People absolutely loved it, and so did we.  So we made it a year-round beer, and it’s now our bestselling beer and our flagship.
Description: Since its introduction, Harpoon IPA has remained unique in its ability to balance hop bitterness with a strong malt backbone. Dry-hopped with Cascade hops, it has a floral hop aroma and a finish that is bitter (it is an IPA after all!) without being harsh or astringent. Combined with a malty sweetness and the fruity esters of our proprietary yeast, those hops create a beer that is wonderfully hoppy but clean and refreshing enough to enjoy a few of - and we hope you do.

Light, crisp, refreshing UFO White follows in the tradition of spiced wheat beers that have been brewed in Belgium for well over 300 years. Brewed with orange peel and coriander, UFO White is the perfect choice for a summer’s barbecue, a night out with friends or any time you're thirsting for something a little different. Like all UFO beers, we leave UFO White UnFiltered.

It’s a simple story; we brew this beer because we like pumpkin (pumpkin pie, really) and thought an unfiltered pumpkin ale would be great, especially during the New England fall.  Turns out it is. Imagine a pumpkin vine wound its way in a field of barley, and a brewer harvested it all to make a beer. Add Northwestern hops and a blend of spices, and you've got UFO Pumpkin. The malt combination provides a smooth body and slightly sweet flavor, which balances perfectly with the earthy notes derived from the pure pumpkin. And like all of our UFO beers, UFO Pumpkin is UnFiltered.

Winter Warmer was Harpoon's first seasonal beer. It was designed to be enjoyed during the holiday season. Note the aroma of cinnamon. There is no aromatic hop added that might overpower the distinct spice scent. A smooth, medium bodied ale spiced with cinnamon and nutmeg.

When we first started thinking of a UFO summer seasonal, 
we knew we had our work cut out for us. We loaded up the 
vans for the beach and spent days “researching” every 
combination of fresh fruit juice and beer we could think of 
until we discovered a combination that made our decision 
easy. Sweet with a hint of tartness, UFO Big Squeeze Shandy 
is perfect for all your summer adventures.
A beer brewed to be enjoyed with summertime activities.  It is light, refreshing, and crisp.

Harpoon Octoberfest is a malty tribute to fall, balanced by a gentle hop bitterness.  In keeping with tradition, it is a Marzen-style beer, brewed with abundant quantities of Munich, Chocolate, and Pale malts. Those malts provide a solid, full body and create the beer’s deep color.  It is a rich, flavorful beer.

This mango-infused Pale Ale begins with a subtle tropical aroma of passion fruit and mango. Golden-copper in color, it has a light body, slight hop bitterness, and malty sweetness, and finishes with a kiss of mango.
The Long Thaw White IPA style blends the spiciness of a Belgian Wit and the American hop character of an IPA.

Harpoon Leviathan Imperial IPA will challenge your senses and your palate. As the vibrant aroma rushes out of your glass you will notice the blend of piney and tropical fruit notes.  At first sip, this big beer starts with apowerful hop bitterness up front and an aggressive hop flavor and character throughout. 

Leviathan Imperial IPA is brewed with tons of pale malt and just enough caramel malt to provide a sweet malt body to balance the hop intensity. We used copious amounts of a variety of hops including Chinook, Centennial, Simcoe, and Amarillo at various points during the boil to create a complex hop flavor and clean lingering bitter finish. We then fermented the beer with Harpoonâ€™s own versatile proprietary yeast.   Finally, we dry hopped at a rate of over 1 lb a barrel to produce this beerâ€™s massive aroma.

We have added natural raspberry flavor to our UFO Hefeweizen to create this beer.  Consistent with the hefeweizen style, this beer is unfiltered and cloudy with a solid foamy head.  UFO Raspberry has a distinctive, hazy rose color.  The scent of fresh raspberries hits the nose immediately, along with a subtle bready aroma from the wheat and yeast.  The body is light and the unfiltered yeast provides a soft mouthfeel.  The taste of the fruit compliments the beer nicely, neither overwhelms the other.  There is a faint sweetness on the palate, which finishes cleanly in a semi-dry, tart finish.

In 2011 Harpoon co-founders Rich Doyle and Dan Kenary brewed a Rye IPA as part of the brewery’s 100 Barrel Series. It quickly became a favorite at the brewery, so we decided to make it year-round. 

This beer is brewed with our proprietary yeast – the same yeast we’ve used since first brewing Harpoon Ale – and some interesting hop varieties. The combination of Pale, Rye, Caramel 60, Flaked Rye, and Vienna yield a complex malt body that stands up to the spiciness of the rye and the pronounced hop flavor. The rye also adds a reddish hue to the beer. The kettle additions of Centennial, Apollo, and Chinook, and the dry hop addition of Falconer’s Flight add a multidimensional hop character.

Harpoon Take 5 was first brewed on the Brewery’s 10-barrel system in early 2014. With each pilot batch the recipe was tweaked until the desired balance between hop aroma and malt character was achieved. This final version begins with a vibrant citrus and pine hop aroma from Simcoe and Amarillo hops and follows through with a sturdy malt profile from the combination of Pale, Vienna, Carapils, and English Amber malts. Hop forward but not too bitter, low ABV but with a significant malt body – a truly sessionable beer.

The unfiltered yeast remains in suspension, giving this style its signature cloudy color and a soft mouthfeel.  Unlike traditional Bavarian hefeweizens, however, UFO Hefeweizen uses a northern German ale yeast to produce it's signature "citrus-like" aroma.

Inspired by the classic tale. Cinnamon, clove, and ginger 
combine with an unfiltered wheat beer in this deliciously 
spiced, gingerbread-inspired beer.

Our head brewer at our Windsor brewery homebrewed a batch of chocolate stout for himself after trying the style at a beer dinner and loving it.  After several Harpooners tried Scott’s batch, we knew that we needed to add this beer to our lineup. It was originally introduced as a limited edition extra in our winter mix pack back in 2008, but it was soon apparent that our drinkers wanted more of this beer (a beer made with chocolate…not too hard to understand!), so we brought it back in 6-packs in 2010.

A chocolate stout is a beer with a noticeable dark chocolate flavor. This flavor is created from the use of darker, more aromatic malt that has been roasted or kilned until it acquires a chocolate color. Harpoon Chocolate Stout is brewed with an abundance of chocolate malt and a touch of chocolate.

This Hoppy Amber Ale is our tribute to the quintessential season of change. A bright hop aroma from late hop additions plays with its strong malt backbone. Amber hued, medium bodied, with hints of citrus and pine, this ale is made for the crisp days (and nights) of fall.

Harpoon Cider is crafted from only one ingredient: freshly pressed apples. We ferment it with our house yeast, yielding a clean but refreshing all natural cider. 
Harpoon Cider is also naturally gluten-free. Its gluten content has been independently measured at less than 20 parts per million, meeting the FDA's proposed threshold for gluten-free.

Having brewed in South Boston since 1987, it was probably only a matter of time before we decided to commemorate St. Patrick’s Day (Evacuation Day - coincidentally a holiday - in Boston).  It’s a beer that we thought would pair well with the late winter as well: malty enough to stand up to the cold but balanced enough to hint at Spring. 

Harpoon Celtic Ale features a deep ruby color, medium body, and a balanced malt bill created by Irish Ale malt and a touch of roasted barley. Rich in tradition and sessionable in character, Harpoon Celtic is the ideal Spring seasonal.
This draft-only Irish stout was made with six different types of malt, including roasted and chocolate, with a small dose of Willamette hops.
Golden and refreshing, flavorful but smooth, with a crisp, dry finish. A balancing act of the finest ingredients for a refreshing new breed of craft beer.
A Double IPA that's slightly sweet with a lingering bitterness.

Locally harvested pumpkins and apples are combined with seasonal spices to craft this pure and natural craft cider.
Harpoon Pumpkin Cider is also naturally gluten-free. Its gluten content has been independently measured at less than 20 parts per million, meeting the FDA's proposed threshold for gluten-free.

Last fall our brewers were improvising a new beer in our 10-barrel kettle. We had some fresh pumpkin puree leftover from a recent brew of our UFO Pumpkin, so the brewers threw that in the kettle with a bit of molasses, cinnamon, nutmeg, and some roasted malts. It turned out to be delicious, so we thought we’d share it with everyone. Half imperial stout, half pumpkin ale, with aromas of dried fruit, chocolate, and freshly baked pumpkin pie, this black full-bodied stout is ready to be enjoyed now or saved for a chilly fall evening.

So many bearded men work here!
Free tastings in theSouth Boston Waterfront brewery weekdays are at 4 p.m.; there is an additional tasting at 2 p.m. on Wednesdays, Thursdays, and Fridays.
The cider is made from apples from Harvard, Massachusetts (about 40 minutes away from the brewery). Makes a delicious brew.

Hot as shweaty bawls in here....no air conditioning!?? Its a 90 degree day in Boston...Get it ogether, Harpoon!!  The only redeeming quality tonight is the parmesan pretzel with marinara...phenomenal.
They only serve beer and pretzels, but that's more than enough to make this a must-visit location next time I'm in Boston. Staff is friendly and barkeeps are more than happy to share Harpoon history.
"Cheese IPA" are the only two words you need to utter when ordering pretzel dips.
Delicious beer and pretzels. Make sure to ask about the rotating pilot batches of beer!! Mmm lemon elderberry ale.
This little brewery is now served all over the country and has 2 breweries (one here and on in Windsor, VT). Take the tour and enjoy some free samples!
The hour long tasting is the BEST!
Coffee porter is delicious. Dark and actually refreshing.
Get the pretzels! And the Triunfo. #beer
FREE tastings every weekday from 2-4pm and weekend tours most of the day for just $5. Boston Beer - the best around.
Go to a beer tasting and reward yourself by tasting the fine beer!

reviews.text: Run by a husband and wife, Bone Up is located within a short walk of Night Shift Brewing. Located in a smaller warehouse space, the taproom itself reminds me of a Coney Island Boardwalk freak show. Brightly colored walls, decor and design-work that hearkens back to the '20s and '30s. There were six different beers on tap for samples, full pours, and growlers. Taking more of a Belgian twist on American styles, there beers are a lot more approachable to everyday consumers and beer snobs alike. There are also snacks available for purchase to quell the munchies. This brewery is one of the younger in the Boston scene, but holds a lot of promise for years to come. If you're in the area, absolutely check it out.
Awesome beer, knowledgeable staff. Small cozy space. Love that even though there's no kitchen, they make an effort to provide snacks and make ordering takeout easy.

This is such a cute little spot! I came here on a Thursday night with a few colleagues and it's so cozy. The staff were so sweet and very attentive.

beers.beerDescription: White Ale with Key Lime juice

There's not much new to say about IPAs since there are five thousand or so other commercial examples out there, but it is a style that's a personal favorite of ours - we tend to prefer hops with the big, fruity, juicy flavors that are all the rage with the young'uns these days. But since this is our mainstay year-round IPA (don't worry, hopheads, we'll have plenty more variations on the style once we're rolling) we've tried to balance that out a bit (for everyday drinkin' we tend to prefer something that doesn't necessarily smell like a fruit salad with perfume on it) with some malty goodness and a dab or two of some slightly-more-nuanced hop varieties (don't get me wrong, we're all about intense flavor. But you wouldn't want an all-syrup Squishee every day, would you?). Needless to say, this is one you'll miss in between pours.

I used to work with a girl named Kelly who didn’t like dark beers until she drank my porter. Then every time I mentioned brewing within twenty feet of her, she’d ask, “Are you brewing your porter?” and then she’d start telling the same story I just told you, only ten thousand times longer. Eventually, I brewed the porter again in the hopes of getting her to shut up about it. It didn’t work, but the beer was a keeper.

Since we like a taste of home in our beers, we set our sights on the fabled Unicorn of American Brewing: a beer that's light (in color/body/etc.) that won't let you down in the flavor department. And lo, we done it! We took a cream ale and goosed it with some good ol' Bone Up magic, and made a tasty brew that'll disappear from your glass before you know it and then you'll have to try and convince your roommate to get you more so you don't have to get up. I’m told that the British call that “moreishness.” There, you learned something today. Go ahead and crack one open, you earned it.

Sometimes you just gotta have an old-school citrus-and-pine IPA, so we took some Classic American Hops and chucked them in the kettle with some Cascade from our friends down the road and mixed in just a *pinch* of Bone Up Magic. We ain't gonna strip the enamel off your teeth, but we are gonna give you a solid beer for solid times. Enjoy.
Light bodied, citrusy dark beer brewed with witbier spices

In keeping with our commitment towards not dumping a bunch of weird goop in our beers, this inky black stout's made with real-ass orange peel and a whole lotta Taza cocoa nibs. It’s a surprisingly smooth sip of suds that gives you a good warm tingle in your belly.
Dark Mild

This jaunty little wheat ale is packed full o' hops and just burstin' with floral notes and whiffs of tropical fruit. This beer is just beggin' to be quaffed as you make the most of these last summer days!

This mutt of a beer is the bastard child of a saison, a double IPA, and a tripel - born by accident and kept by happy coincidence. It has the hoppiness of an IPA, the spicy pepperiness of a tripel, and a fistful of rye. It's a sensorial thrill ride, and we don't think you'll be disappointed.

This is the second entry in our loosely-defined series of single-hop beers made with hops that nobody cares about. This time around we're focusing on Cluster - an old-school American hop that combines lemony citrus character (in times of shortage, it's used as a substitute for Cascade) with a bit of Wild American earthiness. It's a cool lil' hop, and we're showcasing it by using it in a a solid caramel-forward pale ale base that leans a ways toward the red end of the color spectrum.

Somewhat to our surprise, one of the most common requests* we get is for none other than the humble Amber Ale. This caught us off guard for a bit, as it's hardly the most sexy style, until we realized that we'd been entirely missing the point - not everyone wants intense assault on the tastebuds, as is the case with many of these Xtreme Flavor Blast Beerz. Some people want a beer that's Just A Beer - no more no less - so that's why we made this thing! There's some subtle complexity lurking amongst the flavors if you care to look for it, or you can just drink it and not make a big fuss and that's cool too.

Our take on a classic Oktoberfest staple is made to showcase the toasty breadiness of grains we got from Blue Ox Malthouse, as well as some freshass fruity hoppiness from our friends at Four Star Farms. This malty masterpiece ain't gonna disappoint - Prost!

Teamaker hops aren't commonly used in beer - their alpha acids (which contribute beer's bracing bitterness) are so low compared to other varieties (classic hop varieties typically have an alpha acid content of 5-10%, with newer varieties reaching up to 20%. These clock in at 1%) that they're a bit impractical to brew with (most folks make hop tea with 'em, hence the name). But we thought it sounded like a cool little underdog of a hop, and since we didn't know much about it we dumped a big ol' bag of it into a nice, medium-bodied pale ale! This beer's a delightful, curious little thing - these woody, floral aromas are keepin' us bendin' our elbows every time we pour a pint for "research purposes."

After we used Blue Ox malt for Bullhead, we were a bit smitten so we ordered a whole bunch more without really having any plan on what to make with it. Then one day, inspiration struck in the form of a terrible pun, and a plan was hatched. Similar(ish) in spirit to Bullhead, this beer is made to showcase the quality/qualities of Blue Ox malt, heavily featuring their "Vye-Enna" malt to make a light 'n' fruity BDG. Enjoy!

Since we can't get enough of that Blue Ox Malt goodness, we figured we'd test its mettle when paired with fistful after fistful of punchy, fruity hops - the end result is a beer well suited for any weekend activity, whether you're at the discotheque or simply going for restaurant.

While there are some practical reasons why we chose this as our first beer, we care much more about the tasty reasons. We've loaded this with gobs and gobs of the finest hops that Four Star Farms (located in MA!) has to offer, and them hops are braced by solid, bready, slightly sweet backbone provided by Valley Malt (also from MA!).
The latest in our single hop series, Summit smells like a picnic and delivers an all-around satisfying drinking experience.

This is a beer I'd never originally intended to brew more than once, but it ended up being an accidental winner. I had just gotten a bunch of a new hop variety and I wanted to see what it was all about, so I brewed a beer with a really simple recipe so there wouldn't be any other flavors/aromas competing with the hops. And oh man, it was so good. It didn't hurt that I was trying out a cool new hop, but more importantly I'm a big proponent of New Beer Rule #6 - the best beer is the one that was in the empty glass. And considering how fast we went through that pilot batch, I knew it would be silly not to keep using this recipe.

We like a bone-dry saison as much as anybody, but this time around we figured we'd boost the body on this mamma jamma (all the more feels for your mouth) with a fistful of oats 'n rye. Other than that, we went for a fairly straightforward interpretation of the style so we could really let the distinctive character of our house yeast shine through.

BoneUpBrewingCompany.name: Bone Up Brewing Company
BoneUpBrewingCompany.breweryDescription: Our beers celebrate American styles while taking inspiration from old-school Belgian techniques. We brew a few year-round beers, but our gears are always turning, so you can expect a lot of one-offs, seasonal releases, and experimental batches. We love us some brewin', and we think you're gonna enjoy the fruits of our labor!

LamplighterBrewing.breweryDescription: Our goal is to make beer that you’ve never had anywhere else (or at least that you can't find very easily), but beer that is still drinkable and enjoyable. We want to use tradition as a launching point, and add complexity and depth with our choice of yeast and ingredients. Expect to see a lot of Brettanomyces fermentations, a lot of sour, a lot of funk, and a lot of fun. We hope when you see the name Lamplighter on a menu or label, you’ll have a good idea that you’re in for something creative and delicious.

beers.beerDescription: This American-style IPA stands head and shoulders above its hoppy brethren, blending pale and honey malts to balance the palate without interfering in your herbal reverie, and creating a new American classic.

Brewed with Pilsner, CaraVienne, and Rye malts, plus Magnum and Spalter hops.  But the driving force behind this beer is the contribution from whole Black, Green, White, and Pink peppercorns. Added to the brewkettle, these four fab peppercorns harmonize with spicy hops while the malted rye and our Belgian yeast hold down the backbeat.

CBC’s Great Pumpkin Ale is brewed with over 150 pounds of fresh, locally grown, organic sugar pumpkins in each batch, and it has an appropriately distinct orange hue. The subtle fresh pumpkin flavor is enhanced by the addition of a touch of traditional autumn spices, and is guaranteed to please even the most finicky of harvest-time ale fanatics. Come raise a glass in honor of the Great Pumpkin!

Pilsner malt and flaked rice provide sweet cereal grain notes while German and Czech hops add spiciness and a balanced bitterness to the finish. Cold fermented and aged with a German lager yeast, the palate is clean with a snappy finish.

Well balanced, medium-bodied, with a deep amber-red color, this beer's complex palate covers all the bases. A malty caramel sweetness is followed by notes of chocolate and a dry, slightly roasty finish, complemented by a touch of fruity, spicy hops.

You want an IPA, you’ve got one, but with a twist! “Spring Training” breezes in like a breath of fresh air, ready to awaken your senses from a long, cold winter. Crafted primarily of New England-grown pale malts, the recipe also incorporates Belgian carapils and wheat malts to contribute to the beer’s complex body and straw-golden color. Ahtanum and Palisades hops, both relative newcomers on the hop varietal scene, were chosen for their essence of wildflowers and freshly-cut grass, evocative of springtime breezes. This is in contrast to the piney, earthy and resiny characteristics of most IPAs. In addition to extensive kettle hopping the beer is dry-hopped with even Ahtanums to satisfy your hop-craving.
Big and bold, our Pale Ale distinguishes itself by its huge, fresh hop aroma and flavor. A combination of Cascade and Centennial hops gives this beer its nectarious flavor.
CBC's winter seasonal I.P.A.

THE CROWD GOES WILD! A smooth bass line of roasted notes establishes the deep end beneath arpeggios of complex chocolate malt, while power chords of caramelized grain open up to an extended malty jam. Black barley teases treacle character and wades into a velvety sea of oak-derived vanilla and toasted coconut tones. Sustained improvisation of fruitiness modulates to an intense finale, and encores with a rich, espresso-roasted reprise, a capella.

Charles River PorterDeep and dark, full-bodied and robust, our Porter is crammed full of rich, roasted malt character. With underlying notes of fruitness, caramel and toffee, it finishes with a strong hop presence

Barley, wheat, rye and oats combine with hops and citrus peel in this new American saison. Created by men and women who have forged their own paths to craft your beer, here’s a liquid reward for heroic people everywhere who take pride in an honest day’s work.
With elder flowers and dry hopped with Nelson Sauvin.

The best day of the year comes once every summer when the Brew Crew and friends travel to Westport on Massachusetts’ Atlantic Coast to pick fresh heather flowers. After a long day of toiling in the sun, we hustle home and add them to the kettle to create our world famous Heather Ale.Brewed with imported Scottish floor-malted barley, fresh hand-harvested heather flowers are added to the kettle during the boil along with sweet gale and lavender, with a further addition of fresh heather and yarrow to the conditioning tanks.

Every batch of CBC HefeWeizen is brewed with Massachusetts-grown organic wheat, which has been malted for us by our friends in Hadley, MA at Valley Malt. By the way, Weisse (white) and Weizen (wheat) are two interchangeable terms in regards to naming this style, and the words mit hefe (with yeast) indicate that this is an unfiltered beer.

So enjoy your summer with a cold CBC HefeWeizen, and show your support for sustainable, organic farms and small businesses in Massachusetts!

Cerise Cassée is a complex beer in both process and palate. Multiple fermentations begin in stainless steel with our house ale yeast, then spontaneous refermentation and aging along with 300 pounds of sour cherries takes place in the infamous CBC barrel cellar.
Our 26th Anniversary Beer — Barrel fermented wild ale w/ oats, raw wheat and buckwheat. Floral and fruity, notes of pineapple and guava, clean cereal grains, super dry finish.

Brewed in the tradition of the fresh, blond ales of Cologne, Germany, our Golden ale is light in body, crisp and very refreshing. Its soft malt flavor is balanced by delicate, spicy hop flavors and finishes.

Our grisette is a hazy, bright gold from a complex grist of organic pilsner and wheat malts, plus organic oats, rye, and buckwheat. Subtly hopped with Spalt and Hallertauer hops which contribute balance and a hint of floral character, though the grains are really on display. Tart fruity, spicy grain flavors come from the rye and buckwheat and are bolstered by spice notes and hints of citrus from a special guest yeast strain, that of the famous Brasserie d’Achouffe.

beers.beerDescription: Our flagship American IPA highlights the distinctively aromatic Australian Galaxy hop.  The nose bursts with pine, citrus rind, melon and pineapple. Pronounced flavors of peach, clementine, and tropical fruits are accentuated with moderate bitterness and balanced by a light, biscuity malt character.

Our signature American pale ale balances light, crisp, malt character with an abundance of hop-derived aromatics and flavors from the use of Citra and Columbus. The fragrant nose is fresh citrus, tropical fruit, and peach. Bold flavors of pineapple and mango mix with dank notes of zesty citrus and fresh pine needles. With the smooth mouthfeel, gentle bitterness, and dry finish, Fort Point is our standard daily-drinker.

Brewed in celebration of the first anniversary of Row 34, our favorite Fort Point oyster bar and craft-beer purveyor, Vicinity highlights a neighborhood collaboration of passion and vision. Appearance is bright and straw-colored. Spicy, earthy aromas of tropical fruit notes abound. Complex flavors of grape juice, light citrus, and lychee emerge on the palate. The pilsner malt provides a cracker crisp malt character and clean, mineral finish.

In the spirit of tenacity and camaraderie, Mettle was first created to highlight the milestone of our inaugural year as a brewery. With an intense dual dry-hop treatment of Amarillo and Citra, this medium-bodied Double IPA beckons with aromatics of peach and nectarine. A fusion of grape juice and candied citrus greet the palate while accents of white-wine, grassy hop, and a mellow bitterness reveal themselves on a smooth, dry finish. We continue to brew Mettle in recognition of our devoted following of hopheads that have supported us from the very beginning.

This popular edition in our “Street” series of India Pale Ales spotlights the remarkably complex Mosaic hop. Melcher Street is hazy, pale orange in appearance and emits aromatic qualities of grapefruit, mild-earthy pine, and mango on the nose. Dank flavors of pine and green hop, along with juicy notes of tropical fruit, melon, and peach, are accentuated with crisp malt character, mild bitterness, and a soft, effervescent mouthfeel.

beers.beerName: Double Dry Hopped Fort Point Pale Ale
beers.beerDescription: This double dry hopped pale ale contains the same base ingredients, for both malt and hops, as Fort Point Pale Ale, but with an additional dry hop of Citra. The added hops richly enhance the juicy tropical fruit flavors of pineapple/mango, create elevated green, herbaceous aromatics, and increase body.

beers.beerName: Mosaic Dry Hopped Fort Point Pale Ale
beers.beerDescription: With this distinctively dank Fort Point variant we feature Mosaic in the dry hop. Pouring a faintly cloudy, canary gold, Mosaic Fort Point emits a fragrant nose of herbal-woodsy hop, passion fruit, and zesty meyer lemon. Thirst quenching flavors of juicy mango, peppy citrus, and earthy hop entwine on the palate with the familiar biscuity mouthfeel, medium body, and bone dry finish of our signature pale ale.

Our first IPA brewed and packaged at our new facility in Canton, MA.  El Dorado, Citra, and Columbus hops create a blast of citrus zest, pineapple, wet earth, and woody aromatics.  The flavor brings a pithy bitterness and just a touch of toasted malt.  Medium bodied with a dry, minerally finish.

Our Double Dry Hopped version of Melcher Street; this amped up American IPA features a heavy dose of Mosaic hops. The spicy, resinous, herbal aroma bursts with nuances of tart citrus, tangerine, clementine, and subtle green onion. Bold flavors of under-ripe melon, cantaloupe rind, and pineapple are highlighted with gentle bitterness and delicate, biscuity malt character.

Same base grist as Sleeper Street IPA, but with a double dose of El Dorado in the dry hop. These El Dorado hops impart a powerful aroma of distinctive lime zest, along with notes of grapefruit juice, and a subtle woodsy earthiness.  The taste is bright, floral, and citrusy hop upfront and finishes with candied lime. As with all Trillium “Street” IPA’s, Double Dry Hopped Sleeper Street is dry with medium-light body and a crisp finish.

Pot and Kettle with Cold Brew is just one of our many inspired collaborations with Barrington Coffee Roasting Company. With decades of experience hand-selecting and roasting single origin beans from across the world, cold brewed Barrington coffees provide the perfect addition to our signature oatmeal porter. Like a fresh pull of espresso, Coffee Pot & Kettle pours a dark, almost black color with a dense, sepia brown head. Aromas of fresh brewed coffee, nutty cocoa, dark fruits, burnt-caramel, and subtle vanilla waft out of the glass. Moderate in body with medium carbonation; Deep, roasty flavors of cacao, earthy-coffee, mocha, toffee, and dark malt sweep over the palate with an oatmeal-based creaminess and gentle bitterness. To fully explore the wide range of unique aromas and flavors derived from the diverse array of coffees available, we continuously experiment with varying Barrington roasts and blends with each batch of Pot & Kettle with Cold Brew.

UPPER CASE has a delicate, dry pilsner malt character with a smooth, soft, doughy mouthfeel from the raw wheat, oily hop resin which all serves as a canvas for this twice dry hopped 9% double IPA. Overipe mango, pineapple and passion fruit aromas leap out as the beer is poured. The impression of tropical fruit also takes the lead in the flavor which is layered further by white wine, pine resin and grapefruit zest. Hopped primarily with Mosaic with supporting roles played by Galaxy, Citra and Columbus.

Following in the footsteps of our other “Street” IPA’s, Sleeper shares the same base grains while placing the unique El Dorado hop at center stage. Opaque orange-yellow in color with floral aromas of lime zest, grapefruit peel, pine sap, and candied orange. Juicy, hop-driven flavors of bright citrus, melon, and herbal pine are balanced with medium bitterness, fluffy mouthfeel, and dry finish.

beers.beerName: Double Dry Hopped Congress Street IPA
beers.beerDescription: This amplified version of Congress Street IPA is a focused exhibition of the Galaxy Hop. Milky and yellow-orange in appearance, Double Dry Hopped Congress Street emits fragrant aromatics of mango, pine resin, grapefruit, pineapple, and peach. Explosive flavors of tropical fruit, grassy hop, nectarine, orange rind, and creamy malt inundate the palate with a thick, rich mouthfeel and soft, effervescent carbonation. The finish is full and oily, yet clean, with a light, modest bitterness.

The first Double IPA produced at our Canton brewery. Featuring four powerful aromatic hop varieties, Galaxy, Mosaic, Nelson Sauvin, and Columbus, Scaled Up emits dank, spicy, aromas that lead into fruity, citrusy flavors of peach and orange on the palate. Lighter in body than most of our other Double IPAs, Scaled Up finishes dry and smooth with a pleasant bitterness.

Brewed with 30% wheat, this hoppy, golden American ale features Galaxy and Citra in the dry hop. Bright aromatics of overripe peach, orange rind, and green, herbal hops flood the nose while balanced flavors of tropical fruit, citrus, and creamy wheat excite the palate. Refreshingly light bodied with a soft, fluffy mouthfeel, Pier finishes dry with a slightly mineral bitterness.

In another exciting collaborative effort with our neighbors at Barrington Coffee Roasters, we bring you a bold American stout infused with cold-brewed coffee. PM Dawn exhibits an earthy, freshly roasted coffee bean and dark chocolate/mocha nose. The flavor profile consists of vanilla, hot chocolate, and caramel along with rich espresso. With a medium to heavy body, luscious mouthfeel, and light bitterness, PM Dawn is balanced and full, smooth with a drying roast character.

As we prepare to open our new facility in Canton, MA, we release our debut brew: Launch Beer. This special brew signifies a collective milestone for the entire Trillium team. Bright in appearance and light in body, this refreshing pale ale bursts with floral hop aromatics of honeysuckle and passion fruit. Featuring Mosaic/Citra in the dry hop and a crisp Pilsner malt backbone, Launch Beer exhibits graceful flavors of stone fruit and citrus with a satisfyingly sessionable bitterness. We raise a glass to you; the devoted community of supporters who have helped us make our dream a reality!

Same distinctive grain bill as the other "Street" IPA's, but heavily dry hopped with Simcoe. Our treatment of Simcoe results in beautifully balanced aromatics and provides a satisfying depth of hop-driven flavor. Summer Street IPA bursts with scents of spicy pine, lemon, and grape juice while focused flavors of citrus, pear, and essence of pine wash over the palate. Finish is dry with moderate, resinous bitterness.

Our enhanced version of Summer St. IPA features a secondary dry hopping with Simcoe which leads to a fuller mouthfeel, amplified nose, and an intensified depth of grassy, raw hop character. Double Dry Hopped Summer Street is hazy, sunflower gold in appearance with strong aromatics of pine and lemon. Bold flavors of juicy tangerine, pine resin, and green pear dominate the palate with modest bitterness and a dry finish.
3rd Anniversary beer. Double IPA brewed with Sauvignon Blanc grape juice.

Secret Stairs is our signature Boston Stout. Bold and balanced; satisfying with a substantial body, but not syrupy or sweet. Roasted malt provides a nutty, earthy backdrop to bitter cocoa and little hints of caramel. Smooth mouthfeel with a drying sensation on the finish. We brew Secret Stairs to highlight the unique physical connection between Summer Street and A Street. We raise a pint of Secret Stairs to The Fort Pointer; the neighborhood's favorite protagonist!

Brewed in appreciation of The Publick House, a craft beer mecca in Brookline, MA where close friends and warm hospitality welcome us time after time. The Publick House IPA features Citra, Centennial, and Columbus hops with an aroma bursting with fresh orange juice and under-ripe peach along with notes of toasted malt. The flavor profile is more bitter than our “Street” IPAs, but with a toasted, bready malt character to balance. Bitter grapefruit flavors emerge with mild pine on the finish.

The simplicity of Trillium’s grist of barley and wheat delivers a wonderfully complex yet still approachable beer. The house blend of farmhouse yeasts and Columbus and US Goldings hops drive a distinctive character in this rustic, unfiltered ale. A beautiful nose of spice and pepper, coupled with flavors of fermentation-derived fruit and more pepper. Firm bitterness, nicely carbonated with a dry finish, but there’s also a wonderful smoothness in the mouthfeel from the wheat.

Brewed to test the Mettle of our loyal hopheads, this dank, full-bodied double IPA features intense dual additions of Amarillo and Galaxy. Bright aromatics of peach and nectarine fuse with flavors of tropical fruit and grapefruit on the palate. Accents of pine, resinous hop, and a clean bitterness reveal themselves on a smooth, dry finish.

TrilliumBrewingCompany.name: Trillium Brewing Company
TrilliumBrewingCompany.breweryDescription: We are a family owned and operated brewery in the Fort Point Channel neighborhood of Boston, Massachusetts. We created Trillium to realize our dream of bringing creative and flavorful beers to you. These beers are what we envision might have been made today, if a centuries old beer culture had naturally evolved in New England.  To achieve this vision, we stand our craft beers on the shoulders of native ingredients and artisan practices, balancing them with modern-day expertise.

userTips.tip: The 1st brewery to open in Boston proper in decades, Trillium was named 1 of RateBeer's top 10 new breweries for 2013. Tastes, growlers & releases at the taproom; bottles on CBC shelves regularly!

reviews.text: Zagat rated for a reason. Great food, great beer, and the staff is perfect. best Cuban hands down I've ever had to date!

The tasting flight was an amazing deal! Our favorites were the 328 house ale and the pomegranate saison. Brussels were also bomb. Super friendly staff and cool decor. Will be spending more time here for sure.

Great food, great beer. Clean dinning room. Remarkably quiet at times so you can sit down and have a real conversation with people without shouting. Nice addition to the neighborhood and I hope they do well.
Tasty food, super fast service. We had a light lunch. I had an iced coffee, which was perfect, and my husband liked the light summery beer he had. Ate outside on the patio, great space!

Unfortunately, not all the employees understand the notion of customer service. Sadden since the coffee is amazing. Super rude young girl serving coffee this morning. Rolled her eyes at me (she must be in high school?!) for asking for more coffee on a drink she made that was practically milk. She needs to be retrained.

Edit:  Someone addressed that issue with me so professionally and diligently. Shows that perhaps they do take customer service seriously. The place is great and doesn't deserve a bad review for the mistake of an employee.

It's about damn time winter hill got a place like this! 

Breakfast: The bagels are insanely delicious. I don't think I've ever had such a perfectly...

beers.beerDescription: Aromatic notes of pine, resin, papaya, n fresh fruit. Floral n dank.
Light and easy drinking. Slight flavors of malt husk with a moderate aroma, not unlike lilac.
A tour de force of hoppy dalliance
An old world style befriends the pomegranate

Full bodied red with molasses

WinterHillBrewingCompany.name: Winter Hill Brewing Company
WinterHillBrewingCompany.breweryDescription:
Small batch beer made in house, for the house.
Ethically sourced, premium coffee hand-crafted by highly trained baristas.
Small plates, salads and gourmet sandwiches.

reviews.text: Love this brewery! Not only do they have some great brews, recommend doing a few beer flights to discover your favorite, but the space is pretty awesome too. Two large rooms each with their own bar and a fireplace with couches that feels like you are in your own living room. Food truck out front also serves up some amazing food.

Upping Boston's beer scene with a great space, a huge selection of constantly changing brews, and a steady stream of food trucks and events. Great for a quick stop or to spend and an afternoon/evening.
Amazing beer, and it's always changing. Look out for Harborside in the summer, and any other sour they're making. And get food from the Munch truck!
This place was so good.  Our favorite brewery that we visited while in the Boston area!
One of my favorite breweries  in the Boston area. Friendly service, great beer and atmosphere. BYOF is a nice option if you don't like the food truck that parks nearby.
A fantastic brewery/tap room with excellent beers.  Lots of space, easy parking, passionate people.  Most of the food is from a rotating selection of Food...

beers.beerDescription: Soft pale ale bursting with juicy notes of ripe peach and citrus
Bronze Medal Winner in the 2016 World Beer Cup American IPA category, Santilli is a smooth-sipping IPA with massive hop profile. It is crisp, tropical and delicious.
A bright, beautiful hop-bomb. It has a simple, clean malt bill that allows its refreshing blend of citrusy hops to burst through; named after our address at 87 Santilli Highway in Everett
Awake is a robust, lively porter for the senses. Its nose of toffee and cacao leads into rich flavors of coffee roast and baker's chocolate. It finishes bitter with a hint of sweetness
Belgian-style pale ale aged with vanilla beans & fermented with three Trappist yeast strains; zesty hops, gentle malts, and a clean, smooth profile
Berliner Weisse style sour ale aged on strawberries, kiwis, and dried hibiscus flowers.
Named after a Bavarian city, this hefeweizen sips with refreshing notes of clove, banana, and orange rind

Rye ale with agave nectar and habanero peppers. Brewed with rye malts that bring their own natural spice, this invigorating cerveza gets its zesty kick and peppery flavor from habanero peppers that we add after fermentation. Agave nectar, produced in Mexico, helps to sweeten and lighten the body, while our Belgian house yeast strain tempers the beer’s fiery disposition.
Single-hopped IPA with notes of fresh mango, pineapple, and citrus; smooth bitter finish
Gose-style ale brewed with Island Creek Oysters and coriander; tart and briny with notes of lemony citrus, coriander spice, and sweet, savory oysters
Mixed fermentation sour ale aged on Maine wild blueberries and cinnamon sticks
Bourbon barrel-aged porter infused with vanilla beans and coffee beans.
A bright, tart ale fermented with passionfruit! It smells like a rainforest, sips with tons of fruity, citrus flavors, and has a pleasant, wheaty finish.
Bright, crisp, traditional pilsner. Floor-malted German grain delivers soft notes of honey and biscuit, balanced by a floral, zesty hop profile
A Berliner Weisse style sour with cranberries and oranges.
Classic saison with pink peppercorn and orange peel. Sipping with peppery notes of citrus and a dry, crisp finish.

beers.beerName: One Hop This Time: Vic Secret
beers.beerDescription: Rotating single hop IPA series: bright notes of resin, citrus and orange peel. Strong resin aroma

Horchata-style milk stout aged in bourbon barrels with poblano peppers, cinnamon, nutmeg, and vanilla beans; rich notes of chocolate malt, vanilla cream, and cinnamon rolls; a hint of pepper and a splash of bourbon
Stout brewed with chicory root and ginger and cocoa nibs from Taza Chocolate.
Our rotating IPA series: this batch features Topaz, Citra, Cascade, Columbus
Known as Raspberry Simple Sour prior to October 2016. Refreshingly tart sour ale with fresh, juicy raspberries. Gorgeous rosy color, light body and a tart, clean, fruity finish
Rotating single-hopped IPA series: this batch features Topaz hops for juicy orange and apricot aromas with a pleasant bitter finish
Single-hopped IPA bursting with flavors of white peach and juicy red grapefruit. Smooth-sipping, with substantial bitterness and a balanced, resinous finish
Golden ale brewed with holiday spices, fermented with fresh, MA apple cider, and aged in rum barrels.
Mixed fermentation sour brewed with pineapple; bursting with fresh pineapple aroma and flavors; bright notes of Meyer lemon.

NightShiftBrewing.name: Night Shift Brewing
NightShiftBrewing.breweryDescription: Night Shift Brewing was founded in 2012 by a trio of friends with a shared passion for nocturnal homebrewing. Through culinary inspiration and determined innovation, we aim to create memorable craft beers that offer a wide array of unique, complex flavors.

userTips.tip: If you like beer, you'll LOVE Night Shift. The area is a little sketchy, but once you're inside, it's a beer lovers paradise. Try the Rose. Amazing.
Fantastic brewery with a constantly changing tap list of their own craft beers. Become a barrel society member you won't regret it.
They are totally cool with you bringing your own food. Bread and cheese goes great with beer!
The people who work here are awesome. Great place!

reviews.text: Friendly staff and cool community space. We were here for trivia and they ordered pizzas and sold them by the slice at the bar! Made an impression. Their beer is tasty and the list has something for everyone. It's a little hard to find the first time but really nice space to hang out or meet up with a group.
One of the best brewery atmospheres I've ever been to. (The beer is delicious too)

You feel like a regular the second you step foot into aeronaut. This brewery boasts stellar beers, an amazing crew, and innovative/diverse programming. Come for a movie night, lecture, or live music. You won't be disappointed and if they have a sour on tap, it's the best!
Large delicious flights and great space! Loved the atmosphere and throw back video games. One of my favorite breweries from our brew crawl last weekend.

Good beer. Kind of sparse building. There's a lot of open space. When I went, there was  projector connected to an old Nintendo NES. Unfortunately, the console was busted, but the thought was nice. There are also a few arcade cabinets in the back, but nothing special. As for beer, I really enjoyed "A Year with Dr. Nandu" an American IPA. Get it in cans to go! The staff were also incredibly helpful and friendly.
I get the feel that it is a hipster kind of place. There is that familiar yeasty smell of a real brewery.  They have seven beers on tap.   That is a problem...

beers.beerDescription: Mosaic-hopped, hop bursted, and dry hopped reimagination of the first beer we ever brewed, APA "A Session With Dr. Nandu". Characterized by tropical fruit aromas -- especially passionfruit & pineapple -- with bitterness and a clean finish. Available in cans.
Light & hazy, juicy India Session Ale, infused with cold-steeped hops for delicious citrus flavor and aroma with slight bitterness. 2016 Great International Beer Festival Gold Medal, Pale Ales.
refreshing passionfruit, notes of mosaic hops
French-style farmhouse ale, light and spicy
tropical, citrus hops with a smooth bitterness
hoppy Belgian Blond with Nelson Sauvin & Styrian Aurora hops

a traditional London brown porter packed with rich, toasted malts
Brewed with Merlot must and wood aged.
Light and fluffy ROBO-pilsener. 2016 GABF Gold Medalist Classic Pilsner malts give honey and hay notes. A sprinkling of Citra hops lend delicate bitterness and fine, fruity aroma.
Aged with Jack Daniels Oak
Butternut squash rauchbier
Red IPA with rye. Heavily hopped with Galaxy and some Citra & Chinook in the mix.

userTips.tip: Great beer, great space, very hip but not pretentiously so, lots of dogs to pet. A+

reviews.text: Great hidden gem. They brew their craft beers. I'm not a fan of beer, and they were good. The menu options were unique and delicious! They have a variety of events. The employees are nice. And everything is priced right. I'll definitely be going again.

I give this place 3/5 because I believe in rounding up. The beer is fine, an excellent attempt for an ameteurs first try at a specific brew. Flavor profiles don't standout out as described, and no beers stand out against the classics I would love to see on tap at other bars. 

The atmosphere is causal, decor is tasteful but overall the vibe is obviously hipster. Be prepared to wait just shy of an hour for food and tables. 

If you're looking for another spot to add to your barcrawl Slumbrew isn't a bad spot to stop by. But if you're looking for a bar with character and exception, skip to the next suggested bar in better hopes.
Their beer is not only great but their menu pairs nicely. Try their BBQ nachos. You can feel your heart slowing down...in a good way.

Beer is great, environment is relaxed and wasn't overly crowded during the day or at night.  Plenty of board games and chill vibes.  Also had a late night comedy show, which wasn't really our thing, but still cool that it was offered on a Sunday night. Beer is fantastic. Will come back next time I am in Boston.

Nice friendly staff. This is a real working brewery, and you are sitting right in the middle of all the action in visible sight. They have a large selection on draft and a fairly extensive menu with a good variety.
I made my first appearance at Slum Brew on a fine June Friday evening and have been back several times since. Upon entering, I was taken by the  ambiance...

beers.beerDescription: Flagraiser IPA is a big, hoppy tribute to the unfurling of the Grand Union flag atop Prospect Hill in Somerville, MA on January 1, 1776. This ale celebrates our passion for hop aroma and flavor balanced with just the right amount of malt. Huge aroma and resin-y flavors from the elusive Galaxy hops are the signature of this beer. Built on a solid base of pale malts, this double IPA makes generous use of hops from Columbus, Crystal and Galaxy with the Galaxy hops taking the lead during ten days of aggressive dry-hopping.

A refreshingly tart and crisp hefeweizen brewed with local MA wildflower honey, orange peel and coriander, and fermented with the juice from over 1,000 blood oranges. It’s a cloudy, yet effervescent beer, with lingering banana and citrus notes balanced against a healthy wheat backbone and hoppy finish from Mt. Hood and Crystal hops.

Rich black porter with a unique blend of chocolate, coffee, roasted and nutty flavors. Brewed with cocoa powder and conditioned with cacao nibs from Taza Chocolate. Bold flavors from the cacao nibs and black malts are balanced with a special blend of pale malts, oats and wheat to produce a lush and lingering mouthfeel.

A smooth and alluring Belgian golden ale with complex fruity pineapple flavors set against a spicy finish. Dried jasmine flowers added in the boil work with a higher alcohol level to augment Belgian pilsen, caramel and honey malts. Hop character include Chinook and Moteuka hops grown in New Zealand.

An autumn brown ale with distinctive toasty flavors from an assortment of roasted malts and grains. As a seasonal, fall beer, its nutty characteristics offer a great companion to colder climate cuisine. A bright hop finish from Cascade and Fuggles balance the toasted grain notes to create a new expression of autumn brown ales.

It wasn't always his temperament, but they were the ones ... the ones that went looking for him after all. Today is a new day. Lobstah Killah Imperial Red Ale is a special blend of Maris Otter and other malts balance a resiny mix of Columbus, Cascade and Simcoe hops. Our hoppy imperial red ale is the beer of choice for imperial decisions.

LIMITED SEASONAL RELEASE! It's often said there is a better half responsible for making us whole, and so goes the inspiration for this ale. One half of the fermentation is cold lagered and the remaining half is finished as a warm ale fermentation. The result is a smooth and composed imperial cream ale well suited for contemplation.

How many hops are enough for an IPA? We think it's not just quantity, but the blend of varieties as we strive for hoppy delusions in this extremely limited release IPA for the lover of all things humulus lupulus. This beer is light golden in color from pilsner and caramel malts, with a cloudy haze from the addition of wheat. It's an unfiltered compilation of Nugget, Columbus, Zythos, Simcoe and a new experimental hop from the Pacific-Northwest referenced only by HBC-342.

Today, we breathe in deeply. Fresh air and the aromatic essence of Calypso, Ella and Pacific Jade hops fill the air and lighten our hearts while this golden ale lightens our mood. Today is an Island Day. Keep cold, enjoy now for today is the day. Serve at 45º - 50º F

You could gift this bottle as a reflection of your fine craft beer taste, drink it now to ease your holiday tension or cellar for the long winter ahead. For our first year of our Yankee Swap beer series, we selected rum barrels from our friends at Turkey Shore Distilleries and dark maple syrup from North Hadley Sugar Shack. This Strong Ale is a big beer with hints of maple and complex notes of oak and rum from the Old Ipswich rum barrels.
A LIMITED IPA project from Slumbrew Luma Luma is derived from a complex combination of malts, yeasts and hops so this multilayered IPA weighs in at 7.3% abv.
Gose with hibiscus

Summertime is for love, laughter and play, not envy. Never mind those luscious, long climbing vines of spicy, herbal hop cones over there. Sure there is a time for IPA, but today we will be content with smooth and floral Saison. Be happy. Brewed with Belgian aromatic malts, wheat and noble hops. Serve in a goblet or snifter at 45F for optimal enjoyment.

Hopheads go to great extremes in their lupulin quests. It's a worthy endeavor, but fraught with falling across the event horizon in a hoppy stupor. With swirling flavors from both dark malts and the crisp body from pilsner grains, our limited release black IPA will take you to the center of a hop explosion and back, without all the crushing gravity.

Meet Creep. Ever wonder who's responsible for seasonal beers popping up before their time? SeasonALE Creep thinks it's funny to release a pumpkin beer in August or a holiday ale in September. He's a greedy little character, robbing us of time and demanding we move on too soon. We'd be down on Creep, except he brought this refreshing Belgian-style saison brewed with light pilsner malts, wheat and galaxy hops.

beers.beerName: Sittin' On Hop Of The World
beers.beerDescription: "You don’t like my peaches, don’t shake my tree. Get out of my orchard, let my peaches be." Our white IPA is a hybrid ale brewed with wheat malts and fermented with fresh peach puree. The aromatic essence of peach flavors combines with a world of hoppy goodness from Galena, Amarillo and Citra hops.

Limited vertical series 
Belgian Quad aged in oak rum barrels.
Strawberry wheat

Inspired by a less known German brewing style called dampfbier – an all barley malt bill fermented with wheat beer yeast – we found a delicious new expression for our Happy Sol yeast. This beer pours a deep red color with unique malty flavors from roasted barley, Munich, pilsen and caramel malts. A subtle hop spice is derived from German Perle and Hallertau hops.
Our first gourdeous new Pumpkin Beer called Slumkin Pumpkin.
Float Witbier a light, citrusy white ale today.
Hopped up Luma Luma

SomervilleBrewingCompany.name: Somerville Brewing Company (Slumbrew)
SomervilleBrewingCompany.breweryDescription: Make good liquids, make good friends. Since its inception in 2011, the brewery has expanded distribution into six states, achieved annual production of over 2,000 barrels of beer and grown from 2 employees to over 35. The recent addition of two retail destinations to enjoy its core brand of Slumbrew beer with innovative food offerings, along with its own Somerville brewery location are milestones along an exciting path of growth. There are two locations in Somerville MA: The Brewery + Taproom at 15 Ward Street and an outdoor beer garden at Assembly Row.

reviews.text:
I like this place a lot because they brew their own beer, the food is affordable and good-tasting, and when I come here I never have to wait for a table. It is a great place to come for lunch or dinner if you are visiting Harvard square.

There is a dining area where a host/hostess will seat you, but if that is full you can just seat yourself at the bar area and a server will come to you. If you have a large group definitely sit in the dining area. The bar area is generally more busy and a little bit louder, and it sometimes takes a little bit longer for a server to attend to you, but it is worth it if you have a small group and don't want to wait to be seated in the dining area.
Flawless ambiance... great beer, wine and cocktails... and food and attentive waitstaff!
We got burgers and they just were not good. A cold old bun that fell completely apart at the first bite. Not great service. Would not recommend

Surprisingly average food at best despite the hope this would be somewhat of a unique/local pub. To be honest felt very much like a chain restaurant and after looking the place up after I had eaten I discovered that it was acquired by a restaurant chain several years ago.
Surprisingly good food for a pub!  This is a real Boston must to check out.
Definitely my favorite spot to grab a beer in Harvard Square. The menu is very limited (expected, seeing as they brew their own beers), but everything I've...

Sweet caramel malts balance our blend of fall spices

Hop-tastic
